      "value": "Escondido Union is a large elementary (K-8) district in the North Inland region of San Diego County. About 3,091 of its students have an IEP, and 673 of them \u2014 roughly 22% \u2014 have an autism (ASD) eligibility. Around 27% of those autistic students spend most of the school day in a general-education classroom."
    },
    "what_this_means_for_parents": {
      "ai_disclaimer": "This summary was written by an AI model from the data points in this profile. The underlying numbers come from public California government sources, but the narrative is AI-written and may contain inaccuracies. Verify specific claims directly with the school district before making decisions.",
      "ai_generated": true,
      "ai_generated_at": "2026-05-18T03:25:32Z",
      "ai_model": "claude-opus (via Claude Code session)",
      "based_on_sources": [
        "cde_spedps",
        "ca_dashboard",
        "ocr"
      ],
      "value": "About 27% of autistic students in this district are in a general-education classroom for most of the day, with under 1% in a fully separate setting, so many spend part of the day in specialized settings. Among all students with disabilities, a broader group than autism alone, 59% are in general-education classrooms most of the day. On 2024-25 state tests, students with disabilities scored about 102 points below standard in English and 125 below in math, while students overall were 36 and 59 points below. Students with disabilities were chronically absent at about 31% (compared with 23% for all students) and suspended at about 5% (compared with 3%)."
    }
  },
